1) How do you define institutionalized spam? The cheapest and largest spam methods will persist.

4) is a pet issue. It’s one place of many to put spam. Not the cheapest, and designed to be the least harmful.

1. VC money for that has already mostly gone elsewhere. It was a fad like other shitcoin projects. Nobody has to “find” a new hack for witness spam; they’re already published now.

4. That method has been possible in consensus for over a decade. It’s just that people use it now (starting in the months pre-Core30, as you know). Yet it’s being marketed as existential risk now, literally saying Bitcoin will fail otherwise, despite it not being the cheapest way to spam.

@LukeDashjr @youngelonbtc @natbrunell It doesn’t prevent CSAM from being put into bitcoin or materially increase the cost of doing so, though.

If it did, it would be easier to market to noderunners and miners, and might garner more support.

@LukeDashjr @youngelonbtc @natbrunell So you are saying someone cannot break it into chunks, stuff it into the witness, and easily reconstruct it?

1. The tech is already developed and fees are super low. I'm not sure spam will be reduced at all by existing users, but even if it reduces *moderately* then none of this is existential as it's often marketed. Spam could also reduce over time naturally as NFTs/memecoins deteriorate in value and/or if average monetary transaction fees rise from demand (a good scenario, more people transacting in bitcoin).

4. For op return, people have routed to miners through networks of nodes with wider settings than the default, rather than each one having to go directly to miners. You surely know this since I'm not as technical and I know this. Capping op return, as I've said and as you readily admit, still maintains many other methods of spam. For the witness updates, I've never made the claim that every technical detail (or even most technical details) of this fork is bad. In the interview I even said if these rules had been in from earlier, I'd be fine with them. There are several forks out there that I support parts of, which simply haven't garnered enough support for consensus yet. The issue I've raised is marketing the fork as being existential, that bitcoin dies if this doesn't pass, that people who oppose it or ignore it are bad, when ultimately what it does is narrow some methods of spam while preserving many others including the cheapest methods (since it's impossible to cut out all of them).

@MushinTrading @LukeDashjr @youngelonbtc @natbrunell It's still in there and trivial to reproduce from the data.

I support some ways to add frictions/costs to large non-monetary data in bitcoin. What I don't support is marketing them as existential when they only modestly affect it.

